          "body": "Verse 48 is the chapter's theological detonation. Citing Isaiah 66:1-2 — \"Heaven is My throne and earth is the footstool of My feet\" — Stephen denies that God is housed in the temple. The Greek *cheiropoietos* (\"made by human hands\") is loaded: in the Septuagint it translates the Hebrew for idols (Leviticus 26:1; Isaiah 2:18; 46:6). To call the temple *cheiropoietos* is to imply, with terrible precision, that treating it as God's necessary dwelling is functionally idolatrous. This is not Stephen rejecting the temple as such — God Himself had approved its construction (v. 47) — but rejecting the temple-theology that confined God to it. The same God who refused to be confined to the tabernacle has not changed His mind for the temple. Solomon himself knew this (1 Kings 8:27), and Isaiah confirmed it. Stephen is not innovating; he is reading Scripture more carefully than his accusers."
